	<tr>
	
		<td class="msg_user_cell" width="150" valign=top>
		
			 









<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=33357'  class="auth_text"  style="font-weight:bold;" >	
<span style='color:#339999;font-weight:bold; '>DeMorgoth</span></a>
			<br>
			
			<span style="font-size: 8pt;">
			Defender<br>
			
				Posts: 1217<br>
				
				Registered: 05-12-2004
				
			</span>
			


			
			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=33357'>







<img src="http://home.btconnect.com/armoury/Demoicon.gif" border=0 alt=""/></a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&message.id=164859#M164859">1</a> of 23
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 1276 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<div></div><div>Moving past the obvios anger/annoyance of what happened after the latest patch, let's look at what happened, and how it could be avoided/remedied in future. The initial error of pushing the beta vendors to live servers may be just 'sh*t happens', but the lack of contingency plans, and generally lethargic responce compounded the problem by it's inaction. Many more people got caught up in the error than needed to be</div><div></div><div>In the future, how viable would the following be:</div><div></div><div>1: Hard backup of all character data before each scheduled patch</div><blockquote dir="ltr"><div>How much additional time would a complete backup of character data add to a patch? How much additional staffing would it require to implement, or is it just a case or pressing a button and waiting for the data to transfer?</div></blockquote><div>2: Post-patch physical GM hit squad</div><blockquote dir="ltr"><div>Are there resources available to have half a dozen physical, SoE-employed, California based, GMs serverhopping for the hour or two after a patch looking for unusual player clusters or activities in content that might've been changed. They would be able to /kill bugged NPCs, repop zones, or otherwise deal with any unexpected issues related to the patch. They would also have the authority (or be able to instantly contect someone who has it) to bring down the servers and implement a serverwide rollback to pre-patch character data. They can be invis (to avoid the usual 'did you nerf jboots?' tells), they just need to make sure everything looks normal.</div></blockquote><div>3: Variable patch start times</div><blockquote dir="ltr"><div>One of the problems with staffing, especially during the 'unknown staffing requirement' period immediately following a match, would be the unsocial hours patches happen at for the PST based staff. Obviously they'll only have a skeleton staff on during patch times, and especially for short patches. This means that when the servers come up, there are probably still not many people around. Instead of aiming to start patches at 2am or 3am PST, is it viable to push the patches back to such a time that the ETA on the end of the patch is 9am or 10am PST so there are more staff available to deal with any issues that arise.</div></blockquote><div>4: The second a problem like the beta vendors is discovered, make a serverwide announcement stating it is a bug/error.</div><blockquote dir="ltr"><div>This draws an unarguable line in the sand. Once you've announced and /motd'ed the problem, anyone using it from that moment onward is actively and deliberately exploiting (defined as knowingly using a bug for benefit). If you do your utmost to identify the problem, then ignorance is no defense. Make liberal use of 1-3 day suspensions (plus black marks onaccount records) for anyone continuing to exploit after the identification but before you can physically despawn/fix the problem. Make this a very well announced policy change, and the 'honest mistake, guv!' defense will be irrelevent</div></blockquote><div>and before anyone asks, I wasn't online before the vendors got depopped, and haven't bought, traded or looted anything since, Would I have taken part in the feeding frenzy if I had been online? Who knows, but the facts are I wasn't, so I'm not trying to absolve myself of any guilt or responsibility for my actions by blaming SoE.</div>	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
		<td class="msg_date_cell" valign=bottom nowrap>
		<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
		 <span class=date_text>01-19-2006</span> <span class=time_text>03:46 AM</span>
		</span>
		</td>

		
