			>
			<DIV></DIV>
<DIV></DIV>
<DIV></DIV>
<DIV></DIV>
<DIV>I will add&nbsp; two more i posted else where to your list of 4.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV></FONT></DIV>
<DIV></FONT></DIV>
<DIV>#5&nbsp;A beta vendor naming&nbsp;methodology that makes it known instantly this vendor NPC is not supposed to be present on a live server.&nbsp; This will facilitate a faster reaction time by GMs.&nbsp; Such a NPC naming methodology might be "BETA john doe"&nbsp; "BETA sally sam"&nbsp; It might look silly on a beta but a beta isnt intended to be an emersive experience.&nbsp; Combined with a staff policy that any such vendors can be despawned on sight this should facilitate the fastest reaction possible.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV></FONT></DIV>
<DIV></FONT></DIV>
<DIV>#6&nbsp;Stroutrup has a quote that goes essentially: "put in code what you would put in a comment."&nbsp; Instead of just saying a vendor isnt suppose to go live set up the data and the server so that a vendor cant go live unless the person setting up the NPC fails to set up the NPC properly.&nbsp; A simple system in that direction would be a startup file associated with the server where the starting executable detirmined if it was a test server or a live server.&nbsp; And in the NPC data a flag existed that might be "NPC_TEST_ONLY" so that if the flag was set for the data and the server tried to load it into the world it would see the flag and destroy it generating an exception log.</FONT></DIV>
<DIV>Obviously these engineers at SoE are pros and prolly have much more sophisticated improvements to such a simple scheme.&nbsp; But stroustrups advice stands put in code waht you would pu in a comment.&nbsp; So that instead of saying this data cant go live it actually CANT go live unless the person setting it up makes a mistake x2</FONT></DIV>
<P><SPAN class=time_text></SPAN>&nbsp;</P><p>Message Edited by Qutsemnie on <span class=date_text>01-19-2006</span> <span class=time_text>11:40 AM</span>	
