			Piecing together the various comments from devs (so take it for what's it worth), it seems that they do have some checks in place to prevent this thing from occuring. The problem this time was that the data that told which things belonged where was corrupted, so these checks were circumvented (thats the jist of it anyways). Essentially they were completely surprised by this type of error which seems to indicate it hadn't happened previously.<br><br>Its good to know they are using a system to prevent errors of this nature, and while it didn't work this time, I have little doubt they'll be adding more checks to prevent the exact nature of this mistake from happening again.<br><div></div>
